{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "01 — Packages, Structs & Interfaces",
  "description": "The foundation of every Go codebase. This tour walks through internal/llm/llm.go and the start of openai.go, teaching packages, structs, struct tags, slices, and Go's interface system — all through Balaur's own model-provider seam.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/llm.go",
      "line": 5,
      "title": "1.1 — Package declaration",
      "description": "Every `.go` file starts with a package declaration. All files in the same directory must declare the same package name — here `llm`.\n\nThe `internal/` path prefix is enforced by the Go toolchain: packages under `internal/` can **only** be imported by code that shares the parent module (`github.com/alexradunet/balaur`). It's Go's way of saying \"this is private to this repo.\"\n\n**Try it:** rename the package to `llm2` in this file only and run `go build ./...`. You'll get a package-name mismatch error from Go before any other error occurs."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/llm.go",
      "line": 10,
      "title": "1.2 — Struct and struct tags",
      "description": "```go\ntype Message struct {\n    Role       string     `json:\"role\"`\n    Content    string     `json:\"content\"`\n    ToolCalls  []ToolCall `json:\"tool_calls,omitempty\"`\n    ToolCallID string     `json:\"tool_call_id,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nA `struct` is Go's record type. No classes, no inheritance, no constructors — just named fields with types.\n\nThe backtick strings are **struct tags**: metadata attached to fields. The compiler ignores them; `encoding/json` reads them at runtime to map JSON keys to Go fields. `omitempty` means \"skip this field in JSON output if it holds its zero value\" (empty string, nil slice, etc.).\n\n**Key rule:** field names that start with an uppercase letter (`Role`, `Content`) are **exported** — visible outside the package. Lowercase names (`mu`, `chatKrn` in kronk.go) are unexported — package-private."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/llm.go",
      "line": 18,
      "title": "1.3 — Slices",
      "description": "```go\ntype ToolCall struct {\n    ID   string `json:\"id\"`\n    Name string `json:\"name\"`\n    Args string `json:\"args\"`\n}\n```\n\nNotice `Message.ToolCalls` has type `[]ToolCall` — a **slice**. A slice is Go's dynamically-sized ordered collection, equivalent to a Python list or JS array.\n\n- `nil` is the zero value of a slice — it means \"no elements yet.\"\n- `[]ToolCall{}` is an empty (non-nil) slice.\n- `append(slice, item)` adds an element and returns the new slice.\n- `len(slice)` returns the count.\n\nThe `omitempty` tag on `ToolCalls` means a nil or empty slice is omitted from JSON — which is why messages without tool calls stay clean.\n\n**Try it:** in a scratch file, `append` a few `ToolCall` values to a nil slice and print them. Notice you never had to allocate or initialize — `append` handles it."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/llm.go",
      "line": 32,
      "title": "1.4 — The Chunk type and multiple return values",
      "description": "```go\ntype Chunk struct {\n    Content   string\n    Reasoning string\n    ToolCalls []ToolCall\n    Done      bool\n    Err       error\n}\n```\n\nNote there are **no struct tags** here — these fields are never JSON-serialised. Struct tags are opt-in.\n\nThe `error` type is Go's built-in error interface. It has one method: `Error() string`. The zero value is `nil`, which means \"no error.\"\n\nThis struct carries everything a streaming model reply can produce: partial text, reasoning tokens, complete tool calls, a done signal, or a terminal error. A channel of `Chunk` values *is* the stream. When `Done == true` or `Err != nil`, the stream is over."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/llm.go",
      "line": 41,
      "title": "1.5 — The Client interface (Go's most important idea)",
      "description": "```go\ntype Client interface {\n    ChatStream(ctx context.Context, msgs []Message, tools []ToolSpec) (<-chan Chunk, error)\n    Embed(ctx context.Context, texts []string) ([][]float32, error)\n}\n```\n\n**An interface in Go is just a list of method signatures.** Any type that has those methods automatically satisfies the interface — no `implements` keyword, no declaration of intent. This is called *structural typing* or *implicit satisfaction*.\n\n`KronkClient` (local GGUF inference) and `OpenAIClient` (any HTTP endpoint) both satisfy `Client` because they both have `ChatStream` and `Embed`. The `Loop` in `internal/agent` holds a `llm.Client` and can't tell which it's talking to — that's the seam.\n\n`<-chan Chunk` is a **receive-only channel** — the type system enforces that the caller can only read from it, never write. The arrow direction is part of the type.\n\n**Exercise:** Create a type `EchoClient` in a scratch file that always returns `Chunk{Content: \"echo\", Done: true}` from `ChatStream`. Give it the right method signatures and verify it satisfies `Client` with:\n```go\nvar _ llm.Client = &EchoClient{}\n```\nIf it doesn't compile, the interface isn't satisfied."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/openai.go",
      "line": 26,
      "title": "1.6 — Pointer receivers",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (c *OpenAIClient) http() *http.Client {\n    if c.HTTP != nil {\n        return c.HTTP\n    }\n    return &http.Client{Timeout: 10 * time.Minute}\n}\n```\n\n`(c *OpenAIClient)` is a **pointer receiver** — the method gets a pointer to the struct, not a copy. This means the method sees (and can modify) the actual struct in memory.\n\n**Value vs pointer receiver rule of thumb:** if any method on a type needs to mutate the struct, all methods should use pointer receivers — consistency prevents subtle bugs. Look at every method on `OpenAIClient` — they all use `*OpenAIClient`.\n\n`&http.Client{...}` — the `&` takes the **address** of the composite literal to the right, giving you a pointer. `*http.Client` is \"a pointer to an http.Client\". In Go, `*T` is a nullable reference; `T` is a value.\n\nThis method also demonstrates lazy initialisation: if no custom HTTP client was injected, create a default one. The zero value of `OpenAIClient.HTTP` is `nil`, which makes the `if` cleanly readable."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/openai.go",
      "line": 33,
      "title": "1.7 — Error wrapping and defer",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (c *OpenAIClient) post(ctx context.Context, path string, body any) (*http.Response, error) {\n    raw, err := json.Marshal(body)\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"encoding request: %w\", err)\n    }\n    ...\n```\n\nTwo Go idioms visible here:\n\n**1. Check every error immediately.** Go has no exceptions. Functions return errors as values; you check them right away and return early on failure. The pattern `if err != nil { return nil, err }` appears everywhere.\n\n**2. Wrap errors with `%w`.** `fmt.Errorf(\"context: %w\", err)` wraps `err` inside a new error with added context. The chain is preserved: `errors.Is(wrapped, ErrNotFound)` returns `true` even through multiple wraps. Use `%v` if you want the error message as a string but don't need the chain.\n\nConvention: the context string is lowercase, no period — `\"encoding request\"` not `\"Encoding Request.\"` By the time an error bubbles up it reads like an English trace: `\"saving head: minting token: key not found.\"`\n\nAt line 51 you'll see:\n```go\ndefer resp.Body.Close()\n```\n`defer` runs a function when the enclosing function returns — always, regardless of how it returns. It's Go's `finally`, placed right next to what it cleans up."
    }
  ]
}
